Tom,<br><br>
Your reading on Cook's motive for suggesting a lunch meeting with Doc Spatz was right on! It was a move from the extreme right toward the center. It was a breakthrough. That is why I strongly supported it, and still do.<br><br>
Unfortunately, many do not understand the *Marine* philosophy or point of view. Yes, there are many kinds of Marines, and there will be differences in individual expression, and differences in politics, but they all have one common denominator: PRIDE.<br><br>
Cook is a 'Nam Vet Marine. His pride will never falter. He also was there with the rest of us, so he knows the turf and score. While we may not understand his point of view, and perhaps his manner, we would all do well to try to meet him half way. <br><br>
My US Army preparation for Vietnam did not include a sense of pride. I derived some from my ARTY training at Ft. Sill, but not enough to deflect the mess that resides in my head. I once knew a 'Nam Vet Marine with severe PTSD. He still had his pride, to a fault, and I felt it inhibited him from seeking help. That was a tragic extreme.<br><br>
Cook is dealing with the Vietnam War in his own way. Who are we to criticize someone for that which we are doing for <br>
ourselves?<br><br>
As far as Spatz is concerned, he can defend himself. I recall early posts where the &quot;old&quot; Doc Spatz was merclessly brutal himself.
